      "\n      calc\n        (η.arrow X).inv ≫ η.arrow X ≫ G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv = ((η.arrow X).inv ≫ η.arrow X) ≫ G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv := by simp [comp_assoc]\n        _ = 1 ≫ G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv := by\n          have h6 : (η.arrow X).inv ≫ η.arrow X = 1 := by\n            apply LeftInverse.symm\n            <;> exact (h X).inv_left\n          rw [h6]\n        _ = G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv := by simp [one_comp]\n        _ = (η.arrow X).inv ≫ F.homF f := by\n          have h7 : η.arrow X ≫ G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv = F.homF f := h4\n          have h8 : G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv = (η.arrow X).inv ≫ F.homF f := by\n            calc\n              G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv = ((η.arrow X).inv ≫ η.arrow X) ≫ G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv := by\n                have h9 : (η.arrow X).inv ≫ η.arrow X = 1 := by\n                  apply LeftInverse.symm\n                  <;> exact (h X).inv_left\n                simp [h9, one_comp]\n              _ = (η.arrow X).inv ≫ (η.arrow X ≫ G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv) := by\n                simp [comp_assoc]\n              _ = (η.arrow X).inv ≫ F.homF f := by rw [h4]\n          rw [h8]\n          <;> simp [comp_assoc]\n    have h6 : (η.arrow X).inv ≫ η.arrow X = 1 := by\n      apply LeftInverse.symm\n      <;> exact (h X).inv_left\n    have h7 : (η.arrow X).inv ≫ F.homF f = G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv := by\n      calc\n        (η.arrow X).inv ≫ F.homF f = (η.arrow X).inv ≫ F.homF f := rfl\n        _ = G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv := by\n          have h8 : (η.arrow X).inv ≫ η.arrow X ≫ G.homF f ≫ (η.arrow Y).inv = (η.arrow X).inv ≫ F.homF f := h5\n          have h9 : (η.arrow X).inv ≫ η.arrow X = 1 := by\n            apply LeftInverse.symm\n            <;> exact (h X).inv_left\n          have h10 : (η.arrow X).inv ≫ η.arrow X ≫ G",
      "`(η.Y).inv ≫ η.Y = 1`, so we get `(η.Y).inv ≫ η.X ≫ G.f = (η.Y).inv ≫ F.f`. \n\n   *This seems not directly helpful; let's try a different approach.*\n\nAlternative Approach:\n\n1. From `η.X ≫ G.f = F.f ≫ η.Y`, compose on the right with `(η.Y).inv`: \n   `η.X ≫ G.f ≫ (η.Y).inv = F.f ≫ η.Y ≫ (η.Y).inv = F.f`.\n\n2. Now compose on the left with `(η.X).inv`: \n   `(η.X).inv ≫ η.X ≫ G.f ≫ (η.Y).inv = (η.X).inv ≫ F.f => 1 ≫ G.f ≫ (η.Y).inv = (η.X).inv ≫ F.f => G.f ≫ (η.Y).inv = (η.X).inv ≫ F.f`\n\n   *This gives a relationship between `(η.Y).inv` and `(η.X).inv`, but not what we wanted. Hmm.*\n\nAlternative Idea:\n\n1. Take `η.X ≫ G.f = F.f ≫ η.Y`. \n\n2. This implies `(η.X ≫ G.f) ≫ (η.X).inv = (F.f ≫ η.Y) ≫ (η.X).inv`.\n\n   Simplifying:\n   `η.X ≫ G.f ≫ (η.X).inv = F.f ≫ η.Y ≫ (η.X).inv`.\n\n   But again, not directly helpful unless we have more info about the",
